## Understanding the Starter Code

Read all source files before writing a single line of code. The questions at the end of this section are part of the lab report.

### Game Architecture

The project uses three FreeRTOS tasks running concurrently:

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    %% Tareas periódicas
    Input[Input Task\n10 ms]
    Snake[Snake Task\n150 ms]
    Render[Render Task\n33 ms polling]

    %% Estado y sincronización
    GS[Game State\nshared - unprotected]
    Mx[Mutex\ndeclared, not created]
    EG[Event Group\nyou will add this]
    BuzTask[Buzzer Task\nyou will add this]
    TN[Task Notification\nyou will add this]

    %% Hardware
    Joy[Joystick]
    Btn[Buttons S1/S2]
    LCD[LCD]
    Buzzer[Buzzer]

    %% Flujo principal
    Joy --> Input
    Btn --> Input
    Input --> GS
    GS --> Snake
    Snake --> GS
    Snake --> TN --> Render
    Render --> Mx --> LCD

    %% Eventos de sonido
    Snake --> EG
    EG --> BuzTask --> Buzzer
```

The grayed-out elements (mutex, event group, task notification, buzzer task) are what you will add. The arrows between them show the intended data flow when you are done.

### File Structure

**`app_objects.h`** — Declares shared objects using `extern`. The mutex `xMutexLCD` is declared here but never defined or created anywhere in the starter. This is intentional.

**`game.h / game.cpp`** — Owns all snake state:
- `SnakeGameState` — direction, `isRunning`, `needsReset`
- `Position snake[MAX_LEN]` and `snakeLength`
- `moveSnake()` — shifts body segments, updates head
- `ResetGame()` — places the snake at starting position

**`display.h / display.cpp`** — Owns LCD operations:
- `LCD_Init()` — configures the Crystalfontz driver
- `DrawGame()` — clears screen, draws snake
- `drawCell()` — maps a grid coordinate to an 8×8 pixel rectangle

**`main.cpp`** — Wires everything together: clock, buttons, joystick, three tasks.

### Grid System

The LCD is 128×128 pixels. Each cell is 8×8 pixels, giving a 16×16 grid of 256 positions.

```
Cell (gx, gy) → top-left pixel at (gx × 8, gy × 8)
```

`drawCell()` in `display.cpp` performs this mapping for you.

<p align="center">
  <img src="/assets/images/snakeGrid.png" alt="Snake Grid Representation" width="300"/>
  <br />
  <sub>Snake Grid — 16×16 cells, each 8×8 pixels</sub>
</p>

### Snake Representation

```c
Position snake[MAX_LEN];  // array of {x, y} grid coordinates
uint8_t  snakeLength = 4; // number of active entries
```

- `snake[0]` is the **head** (green)
- `snake[1]` through `snake[snakeLength-1]` are body segments (yellow)

### Movement Logic

`moveSnake()` does two things each game tick:

**1. Shift the body:** each segment copies the position of the one ahead of it.

```c
for (uint8_t i = snakeLength; i > 0; i--) {
    snake[i] = snake[i - 1];
}
// After this loop: snake[0] still holds the OLD head position.
```

**2. Move the head:** update `snake[0]` based on `currentDirection`. The starter wraps around edges (no wall collision yet).

**How growth works:** if you increment `snakeLength` after the shift — before overwriting anything — the body-shift already copied data into `snake[snakeLength]`, so you get one extra segment for free on the next tick.

