## Core Concepts

### Common FreeRTOS Pitfalls

Before coding, know these failure modes:

**Forgetting to release a mutex:**
```c
// WRONG — if you return early, the mutex is never released
xSemaphoreTake(xMutexLCD, portMAX_DELAY);
if (errorCondition) return;   // mutex leaked
xSemaphoreGive(xMutexLCD);

// CORRECT — check preconditions before taking
if (errorCondition) return;
xSemaphoreTake(xMutexLCD, portMAX_DELAY);
// ... do work ...
xSemaphoreGive(xMutexLCD);
```

**Delaying while holding a mutex:**
```c
// WRONG — blocks all other users for 1 second
xSemaphoreTake(xMutexLCD, portMAX_DELAY);
DrawGame();
vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(1000));   // still holding the mutex!
xSemaphoreGive(xMutexLCD);

// CORRECT — release first, then delay
xSemaphoreTake(xMutexLCD, portMAX_DELAY);
DrawGame();
xSemaphoreGive(xMutexLCD);
vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(1000));
```

**Calling regular FreeRTOS functions from an ISR:**
```c
// WRONG — xQueueSend inside an ISR will corrupt the kernel
void GPIO_ISR(void) {
    xQueueSend(myQueue, &data, 0);
}

// CORRECT — use the FromISR variants
void GPIO_ISR(void) {
    BaseType_t woken = pdFALSE;
    xQueueSendFromISR(myQueue, &data, &woken);
    portYIELD_FROM_ISR(woken);
}
```

<Aside type="caution" title="Priority inversion">
If a high-priority task waits for a mutex held by a low-priority task, a medium-priority task can preempt the low one and delay the high one indefinitely. FreeRTOS mutexes use **priority inheritance** to prevent this. Binary semaphores do not. This is one reason to use `xSemaphoreCreateMutex()` instead of `xSemaphoreCreateBinary()` for resource protection.
</Aside>

### What is a Mutex?

A mutex prevents two tasks from accessing a shared resource simultaneously. Unlike a binary semaphore, a mutex has **ownership** (only the taker can give it back) and supports **priority inheritance**.

Use a mutex when multiple tasks share: the LCD, a UART, an SPI bus, or any multi-field data structure that a task could read mid-update.

For more details, see:
<LinkCard
     title="Semaphores and Mutexes Guide"
     description="Mutex vs. binary semaphore, priority inheritance, and correct usage patterns."
     href="/guides/freertos/semaphores-mutexes/"
     icon="right-arrow"
/>

### What are Task Notifications?

A task notification is a lightweight signal sent directly to one specific task. Unlike a semaphore, it requires no kernel object — every task already has a built-in notification counter.

```c
// Sender (from another task)
xTaskNotifyGive(xTargetTaskHandle);

// Receiver — blocks until notified
ulTaskNotifyTake(pdTRUE, portMAX_DELAY);
```

Task notifications are faster and smaller than semaphores for 1:1 signaling. You will use them to wake `vRenderTask` exactly when the game state changes, instead of waking it every 33 ms regardless.

For more details, see:
<LinkCard
     title="Task Notifications Guide"
     description="xTaskNotifyGive, ulTaskNotifyTake, and when to prefer notifications over semaphores."
     href="/guides/freertos/task-notifications/"
     icon="right-arrow"
/>

### What are Event Groups?

An event group holds a set of boolean flags (bits). Any task can set or clear any bit. Any task can block until one or more specific bits are set.

```c
// Define named bits
#define EVT_FOOD_EATEN  (1 << 0)
#define EVT_GAME_OVER   (1 << 1)

// Setter (from any task)
xEventGroupSetBits(xGameEvents, EVT_FOOD_EATEN);

// Consumer — blocks until ANY of the listed bits are set
EventBits_t bits = xEventGroupWaitBits(
    xGameEvents,
    EVT_FOOD_EATEN | EVT_GAME_OVER,
    pdTRUE,        // clear matched bits after returning
    pdFALSE,       // wake on ANY bit (not all)
    portMAX_DELAY
);
```

One event group replaces multiple semaphores when a consumer cares about *which* event happened, not just *that* something happened.

For more details, see:
<LinkCard
     title="Event Groups Guide"
     description="xEventGroupCreate, xEventGroupSetBits, xEventGroupWaitBits — patterns and pitfalls."
     href="/guides/freertos/event-groups/"
     icon="right-arrow"
/>

### Task Priorities

| Task | Suggested Priority | Reasoning |
|------|-------------------|-----------| 
| Input | 3 | User input must never be delayed by game logic |
| Snake | 2 | Game logic runs after input is processed |
| Render | 2 | Draws whenever Snake notifies it |
| Buzzer | 1 | Audio feedback is non-critical |

<Aside type="tip">
Start all tasks at priority 2 and adjust only if you observe responsiveness problems.
</Aside>

